description:
The Philadelphia man who robbed another man of a bag of rock as part of a social media prank is facing jail after police failed to see the funny side of it.

Daron Stinson, 21, likes to do crazy stuff which he films and then posts on his Instagram account.

Last week, Stinson and a buddy stopped alongside a 52-year-old man on Diamond Street near Sedgely and pointed a gun at the man, threatening to shoot him if he did not hand over a bag of rock salt. 

Then he posted the short to his Instagram account to share with his friends.

Only the Philadelphia police department didn't see the funny side of the clip, with one officer saying Stinson and his pals could have "caused someone to have a heart attack."

Stinson turned himself into police after the clip was featured on local news and despite the fact that the weapon he used turned out to be a pellet gun he has subsequently been charged with aggravated assault, conspiracy, making terroristic threats, possession of an instrument of a crime, simple assault and recklessly endangering another person.

Stinson was arraigned and his bail was set at $250,000. He is scheduled to appear in court on March 6th.

description:
Elon Musk's high-profile battle to sell Tesla cars directly to consumers is just the latest challenge to state laws that give an advantage to powerful local businesses, even if the legislative justification is difficult to ascertain. Musk
told Tesla shareholders last year such laws are a "perversion of democracy,"
as noted by the New York Times. He joins a growing chorus of critics who are challenging laws that protect car dealers, taxi services, funeral directors and many other industries under the guise of public safety or economic regulation. In many cases those laws represent the fruits of lobbying by powerful economic interests — how many legislators
don't have an auto dealer in their district? — and result in consumers paying higher costs or narrower choices.


http://www.forbes.com/sites/danielfisher/2014/03/18/teslas-elon-musk-learns-an-old-lesson-fighting-protectionist-dealer-laws/
http://www.wochit.com
title: Tesla's Elon Musk Learns An Old Lesson Fighting Protectionist Dealer Laws

description:
Song # 1184 from Our Gospel In Song Collection by Col Johnston. The Book of Proverbs is a collection of moral and religious teachings, mostly in the form of short sayings, dealing with everyday concerns, including good manners and common sense. Much of the advice in Proverbs is still relevant to us today.
Call out for insight and cry aloud for understanding (Proverbs 2:3). Then you will understand the fear of the Lord and find the knowledge of God (Proverbs 2:5). For the Lord gives wisdom, and from His mouth come knowledge and understanding (Proverbs 2:6). He holds victory in store for the upright, He is a shield to those whose walk is blameless (Proverbs 2:7). For He guards the course of the just and protects the way of His faithful ones (Proverbs 2:8). Then you will understand what is right and just and fair, every good path (Proverbs 2:9). For wisdom will enter your heart, and knowledge will be pleasant to your soul (Proverbs 2:10). Discretion will protect you, and understanding will guard you (Proverbs 2:11). Wisdom will save you from the ways of wicked men, from men whose words are perverse (Proverbs 2:12). Men who leave straight paths to walk in dark ways (Proverbs 2:13). Men who delight in doing wrong and rejoice in the perverseness of evil (Proverbs 2:14). So walk in the ways of good men and keep to the paths of the righteous (Proverbs 2:20). For the upright will live in the land, and the blameless will remain in it (Proverbs 2:21). But the wicked will be cut off from the land, and the unfaithful will be torn from it (Proverbs 2:22).
Thought for today: trust in God today and prepare for your tomorrow.
Thought for the future: a Christian's inheritance is guaranteed forever. Where will you spend your eternity?
title: #1184- The Lord Gives Wisdom

description:
Fussy tea REALLY annoys me but this one is meant to help you get to sleep so I thought I would give it a whirl. It has an over the top name for something that is £1. It is called Knightsbridge but is not from Harrods as the price would have been maybe £20. It is actually from Lidl which is polar opposite to the clientele of Harrods. I would love to review Harrods Camomile Tea but I am not going all the way into Knightsbridge for one item but I am going to try to review "upmarket" food and drinks soon!

I did review Selfridges chocolate but even by my standards the edits in the video were awful to I didn't upload it.

Americans and other places around the world think all the English do is drink tea all day which is in fact true to some extent but we do lots of other stuff too. I don't actually like tea or coffee and only if I have to I drink it cold with loads of milk and Canderel.

I don't think these teabags will be used in a hurry though!
title: FIRST REVIEW Knightsbridge Camomile tea Lidl 3mins 20secs

Richard is also the UK Trade & Investment's Special Representative for Kuwait, assisting in the Government's policy on the promotion of bilateral business and trade development between these countries and a Fellow of the Chartered Institute for Securities & Investment. In 2011, Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II bestowed Richard with the honour of OBE, for civic excellence in duties for the UK Islamic finance industry.

description:
A 57-year-old woman was referred to the ophthalmologic department with subacute blindness of the left eye. This was preceded by headaches, nausea, transient diplopia, 3rd cranial nerve palsy and gait imbalance since six months. On admission the right eye had a normal visual acuity and visual fields. Unfortunately, the vision decreased to counting fingers and she developed an altitudinal scotoma. 
Amongst others, the MRI of the brain showed a pachymeningitis with compression of both intracanalicular optic nerves, resulting in a wide subarachnoid space around the infraorbital part. Further investigation prompted the diagnosis Wegener's granulomatosis and the patient was treated with high dose corticosteroids. This temporary improved her vision, only to decrease again after cessation of medication. With the eminent blindness of her only functional eye, surgical decompression of the right optic nerve over the course of the optic canal was performed via a pretemporal approach with anterior clinoidectomy. The dura was excised and histology confirmed the diagnosis morbus Wegener. The postoperative course was uneventful and the patient's visual acuity on her right eye almost totally recovered, as well as the visual fields. Even after cessation of high-dose corticosteroids this remained the case.
Surgery by: dr. R. Dammers and dr. I. Haitsma, department of neurosurgery, Erasmus MC, Rotterdam, the Netherlands.
Video editting by: dr. V. Volovici.
title: Optic nerve decompression in a case of hypertrophic pachymeningitis due to Wegener's granulomatosis

Altors summary:
Following the murder of their legal guardian, two best friends suffer the thing they fear most, separation. Solenum and Calycanthus must take the adventurous paths of finding their way back to one another, and as they do so, they will uncover the secrets their land has been hiding beneath a carefully constructed facade for centuries.

An underground war is taking place, kept hidden from the public eye by those called the Altors and Regius. Although unaware at first of what their involvement brings to the people of Zinc, Calycanthus Esquivel's close proximity to the Altors allows him to uncover parts of the truth, creating an important turning point that may just be the kick the Altors need to beat the Regius. But it is Solenum Everhart who will find the possible key that can lead to a peaceful future. Is Galax Kaminski an exception to the rule that says all Regius are cruel at the core? Will Solenum be able to show him that he may just be the example everyone needs in order to end the hidden turmoil?

While Solenum and Calycanthus change the lives of so many, their new environments forces them to grow, come face to face with danger, death, family connections and just a touch of magic. New friendships are made and love is found as the two best friends work hard on finding their way back to one another throughout a world they always lived in, but was a mystery up until now.

description:
Gezien - Heb je het ooit als eens zó bekeken?
Een tent van drie bij zes meter staat midden in een festivalsetting op een grasveld. Eromheen bomen en bezoekend publiek. Om de 20 minuten mogen tien mensen naar binnen. Zij nemen plaats op bankjes en kijken naar een tegenoverliggende wand. Wanneer de muziek begint starten ook beelden van buiten op de wand: Het festivalterrein. Soms snel, soms langzaam. De bomen, het gras. De mensen: voeten, handen, gezichten. Eén of meer. De tocht door het park is live te volgen en dat doet ook een danseres die in de tent al dansend kijkt naar de projectie. Haar bewegingen vloeien samen met de beelden of contrasteren ermee. Via haar bekijken de toeschouwers de projectie die daadwerkelijk live worden gemaakt. Dus het bankje waar net nog gerust werd, dat meisje met haar moeder, dat pad tussen de bomen door. Daar zijn de toeschouwers net nog geweest: Het publiek werpt een andere blik op de wereld waarin zij zich net nog bewoog.
title: Eye-Wash Productions: Gezien - Heb je het ooit als eens zó bekeken?

description:
In the sixth episode of a series of videos that explore the Rodgers and Hammerstein collections at the Library of Congress, Michael Feinstein examines the origins of the opening number from the hit musical Carousel, "Carousel Waltz." Produced by special arrangement with Imagem/Williamson Music Inc. 

Speaker Biography: Michael Feinstein, the multi-platinum-selling, two-time Emmy and five-time Grammy-nominated entertainer, dubbed "The Ambassador of the Great American Songbook," is considered one of the premier interpreters of American standards. His 200-plus shows a year have included performances at Carnegie Hall, the White House, Buckingham Palace, Sydney Opera House and the Hollywood Bowl. Feinstein has received national recognition for his commitment to celebrating America's popular song and preserving its legacy for future generations. In 2007, he founded the Michael Feinstein Great American Songbook Initiative, dedicated to celebrating the art form and preserving it through educational programs, as well as the annual High School Vocal Academy and Competition. Michael serves on the Library of Congress' National Recording Preservation Board. 

For transcript, captions, and more information, visit http://www.loc.gov/today/cyberlc/feature_wdesc.php?rec=6329
